4.2 Experiment 15: Insertion Sort


Objective
To understand the working and advantages of Insertion Sort

Key Features
ď‚· Time Complexity:
o Best Case: O(n) (nearly sorted array)
o Worst Case: O(nÂ˛)
ď‚· Stable sorting algorithm
ď‚· Efficient for small or nearly sorted datasets


Conclusion
Insertion Sort performs very well when the input is already almost sorted.

4.3 Experiment 16: Merge Sort


Objective
To implement divide-and-conquer sorting.


Key Features
ď‚· Time Complexity: O(n log n)
ď‚· Stable sorting algorithm
ď‚· Uses extra space (O(n))


Working
ď‚· Divide array into halves
ď‚· Sort each half recursively
ď‚· Merge sorted halves


4.4 Experiment 17: Quick Sort

Objective
To study partition-based sorting.


Key Features
ď‚· Average Time Complexity: O(n log n)
ď‚· Worst Case: O(nÂ˛)
ď‚· Not stable
ď‚· In-place sorting (no extra space needed)


Concept
ď‚· Choose a pivot
ď‚· Partition elements
ď‚· Recursively sort partitions


4.5 Experiment 18: Heap Sort


Objective
To understand heap-based sorting.


Key Features
ď‚· Time Complexity: O(n log n)
ď‚· Not stable
ď‚· Uses Heap Data Structure


Working
ď‚· Build max heap
ď‚· Extract elements one by one
ď‚· Place them in sorted order


